#: src/pages/docs/concepts/LatencyPage.tsx:28
msgid "Glass-to-glass latency is the time from light hitting a camera sensor (\"first glass\") to the picture appearing on a display (\"second glass\"). It is a chain of small budgets, and every hop adds some: the camera's own encoder, the network transport, any receive/jitter buffering, decoding, compositing, re-encoding the canvas, the output transport, and finally the viewer's player buffer. No single component \"is\" the latency — the chain is."
msgstr ""

#: src/docs/registry.ts:447
msgid "Glass-to-glass latency, what each protocol adds, and the trade-offs against robustness."
msgstr ""

#: src/pages/docs/concepts/ResiliencePage.tsx:115
msgid "Glitchy, corrupt, and malformed inputs are the expected workload, not an edge case: decode errors on one stream are tolerated and recovered per tile, and a broken track inside a transport (for example a damaged subtitle rendition) is warned about and recovered without killing the streams alongside it."
msgstr ""

